The Jordan family were once a happy crowd
The family of six lived in a council house Just outside London But something went wrong
Mother and father were always shouting at each other the people across the street could hear them fighting the children would cry Tommy was the oldest he was 12 he was more grown up that than the others
Jane was 8 she was frightened of her mum and dad Joan was 5 and Alan 1 1/2 years
He was too young to to understand he was crying all the time nevertheless

It happened to me When I was 4 years old I very nearly died
It was one sunday when my 3 older sisters and I were out for a walk I had my photo taken near a brook
I still have the photo
The brook was about 8 feet wide
The water was about 2 feet deep
But there was 6 feet of wet slimy mud I was the first to cross the bridge it broke and in I went
I slowly sank in the mud my 2 youngest sisters ran home but my oldest sister stopped and saved my life she held my head above water until my sisters got home and told my parents
then they raced down to the brook dad had a hell of a Job pulling me out as the mud held me down eventually he got me out and carried me home
my clothes had to be destroyed it took seven baths to get me clean

I'm am never allowed to sit up and watch programmes not suitable for children one night when dad was digging the garden mum had gone out, there was a film on TV unfit for children I sat and watched it, it was all murder and killing, men were being hung and others were being shot or stabbed
men had their heads cut in half

My work on a farm I have live on a farm all of my life, I am not boasting but I think I know a fair bit about farming
I know most about cattle and only a little about machinery
Some people say farming is the lowest paid and hardest working employment out
I agree with those people
but I would rather work for my living, than just sitting in a stuffy old office adding up numbers all day or whatever they do
Give me the open air life
My father is a farm stockman and I hope to take on the same Job when I leave school
I am going to take my apprenticeship course when I leave at easter
that means that I go to classes once a week
I will learn a lot more about farming and if I pull through the course I will be a useful chap about the farm
While I am taking my course I will be getting 17 shillings less than the boy worker that is not taking the course
But when I am 17 and finished my Apprenticeship I will get 10% more than the average pay of a boy my age
Many people asked me why I have chosen farming as my future career
(1) I will be in the open air
(2) I will be doing a different Job every day (3) I am not interested in anything else
For the last 2 or 3 years I am have been working on the farm in the holidays
And I can tell the men I have worked with have been good and given me a few tips
my dad has told quite a lot about farming which I know will help when I leave school
So if anybody wants an open air life, choose FARMING

